DATA 299: Data Management with dplyr

Recall, the tidyverse contains useful packages for managing and visualizing data such as

  • dplyr (data verbs for managing data)
  • ggplot (plots)

The package ggplot gives us nice functions for creating graphics. More on that later. The package dplyr, which is designed to help us intuitively tackle data frame manipulation tasks via a collection of data verbs:

dplyr command Description
select() selecting columns (variables)
filter() filter (subset) rows
mutate() create new variables (columns)
group_by() group the data
summarize() summarize or aggregate the data
arrange() sort the data
join() joining data frames
recode() recoding a variable

I encourage you to reproduce all of the results on this page in your own RStudio session.

The Rectangles data

Inspired by a data table of first names, I created some rectangles in my laboratory. I gave them names, handedness, dimensions, and a color. In short order I had a veritable village of rectangles. To meet this friendly lot, load them into your session:

df <- read.csv("https://mphitchman.com/stats/sports/data/rectangles.csv")

Heres one way to get a quick look:

summary(df)
##      Name               length           width          color          
##  Length:600         Min.   : 3.710   Min.   :11.50   Length:600        
##  Class :character   1st Qu.: 7.530   1st Qu.:12.26   Class :character  
##  Mode  :character   Median : 8.890   Median :13.02   Mode  :character  
##                     Mean   : 8.933   Mean   :12.98                     
##                     3rd Qu.:10.320   3rd Qu.:13.65                     
##                     Max.   :16.130   Max.   :14.49                     
##                                      NA's   :8

The data frame has 600 rectangles and 4 variables associated with them: their Name (which gives name and handedness), length, width, and color. Notice, Name and color are categorical variables, and length and width are numerical. Notice also that width has a few missing values.

We will spend time discussing ways to handle missing values. One approach is to delete rows with missing values. Here, we replace missing width values with the mean width.

We can see which rows have missing width values:

df[is.na(df$width),]
##             Name length width  color
## 55    Brinda (L)   9.27    NA   blue
## 56     Malia (R)   5.80    NA orange
## 189 Rayfield (R)  10.16    NA  green
## 195  Trenten (R)   9.28    NA    red
## 224    Flint (R)   7.84    NA yellow
## 252  Beckham (R)  10.18    NA  green
## 282    Dwane (R)   7.82    NA  green
## 377   Yareli (R)   6.16    NA yellow

and we compute the average of the recorded widths as follows:

mean(df$width, na.rm=T)
## [1] 12.98125

We assign this average value to the missing width cells as follows:

df$width[is.na(df$width)] <- mean(df$width, na.rm = T)

Intro to dplyr

To access the functions in dplyr, our data management package of choice, we load the tidyverse into our session:

library(tidyverse)

The key to using dplyr is the pipe command |>, which I read as then, followed by an action, such as filter() or select(), which we discuss below. Alternatively, the pipe command can be written as %>%.

For instance, if I came across the following code

lego |> filter(pieces > 500) |> arrange(desc(cost))

I would read it as follows: take the lego data set, then filter it to include just those lego sets with more than 500 pieces, and then arrange these sets by how how much they cost, in descending order. Of course, the code above assumes I have a data frame entitled lego having columns named pieces and cost.

Heres a list of dplyr data verbs we consider below.

dplyr command Description
select() selecting columns (variables)
filter() filter (subset) rows
mutate() create new variables (columns)
group_by() group the data
summarize() summarize or aggregate the data
arrange() sort the data
join() joining data frames
recode() recoding a variable

Filter (rows)

We use the filter() verb to find those rows (observations) that meet some criterion for a variable.

For instance, the following code returns all rectangles in df having length at least 15 and sorted by length in descending order. There are just 2!

df |> filter(length >= 15) |> arrange(desc(length))
##        Name length width  color
## 1 Dasia (R)  16.13 14.48 orange
## 2   Son (R)  15.96 13.47 yellow

Note: We use the double equal signs == when we are searching for entries that match a particular value or character. We use a single equal sign (e.g., x = 4) to assign a value or character to a variable.

Note: We can filter on multiple conditions at once.

To filter on those rows in which BOTH cond1 and cond2 apply, we can write

df |> filter(cond1 & cond2) or df |> filter(cond1, cond2).

To filter on those rows in which either cond1 or cond2 applies, we write

df |> filter(cond1 | cond2)

Question: List all rectangles that are yellow and have length at least 14

df |> filter(color=="yellow", length >= 14)
##            Name length width  color
## 1 Maryellen (R)  14.68 12.60 yellow
## 2       Son (R)  15.96 13.47 yellow
## 3     Suzie (R)  14.62 12.48 yellow

Separate (a column)

If I want to filter rectangles according to their handedness it would be convenient to separate a rectangles handedness from its name. That is, handedness should be its own column in the data frame.

The following command redefines the data frame df after separating the handedness from the name column

df <- df |> separate(Name,into=c('Name','Hand'),sep=" ",remove=TRUE)
head(df,4)
##       Name Hand length width  color
## 1   Linnie  (R)  10.70 13.74 yellow
## 2    Hyrum  (L)   7.92 11.83   blue
## 3   Emmett  (R)  11.60 13.38    red
## 4 Georgina  (R)   9.46 14.49  green

Unite (columns)

Incidentally, this process is reversible via the unite() command:

df |> unite('Name',Name:Hand,sep=" ",remove=TRUE) |> slice(1:4)
##           Name length width  color
## 1   Linnie (R)  10.70 13.74 yellow
## 2    Hyrum (L)   7.92 11.83   blue
## 3   Emmett (R)  11.60 13.38    red
## 4 Georgina (R)   9.46 14.49  green

Notice that in the preceding code chunk I did not redefine df here, I simply displayed the result of uniting the columns, so the data frame df stays as defined in the code chunk above in which we separated handedness from name:

head(df,4)
##       Name Hand length width  color
## 1   Linnie  (R)  10.70 13.74 yellow
## 2    Hyrum  (L)   7.92 11.83   blue
## 3   Emmett  (R)  11.60 13.38    red
## 4 Georgina  (R)   9.46 14.49  green

Mutate (new columns)

The mutate command can be used to create new columns.

For instance, we can create a perimeter column and an area column from the length and width columns. I will redefine the data frame so that we carry these new columns along with us as we go.

df <- df |> mutate(area = length*width,
                   perimeter = 2*length + 2*width)

Question: Find the average area of all green, left-handed rectangles.

mean((df |> filter(color=="green" & Hand == '(L)'))$area)
## [1] 123.8571

The overall average area is 115.85, so green lefties, on average, tend to have slightly larger area.

Select (columns)

We can select() certain columns to display (and choose the order in which to display them). Perhaps we just want to report the names and perimeters of the 10 largest (in terms of area) green lefties? No sweat!

df |> 
  filter(color=='green',Hand=='(L)') |> 
  arrange(desc(area)) |>
  select(Name,perimeter) |>
  head(10)

Summary statistics by group

Task: Create a new data frame called df_by_color that groups the rectangles by color and records the following:

  1. how many rectangles of each color type,
  2. the mean area of rectangles of each color, and
  3. the standard deviation of the areas in each color group
df_by_color <- df |> 
  group_by(color) |>
  summarize(N=length(color),
            avg=mean(area),
            stdev=sd(area))
df_by_color
## # A tibble: 5  4
##   color      N   avg stdev
##   <chr>  <int> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 blue     121  110.  27.7
## 2 green    114  116.  27.8
## 3 orange   124  118.  28.0
## 4 red      116  118.  24.5
## 5 yellow   125  117.  27.7

Note: This is a very useful thing to do. Often we will want to find the sample mean, sample size, and sample standard deviation across different groups like this.

Heres a nice display of these summary statistics, which uses the package kableExtra, and also rounds the means and standard deviations to 2 decimal points:

library(kableExtra)
df_by_color |> 
  kbl(digits=2) |>   
  kable_classic(full_width=FALSE,
                position="left")

blue 121 110.42 27.73
green 114 116.31 27.82

Join (data frames)

We will have occasion to join two different data frames that are linked by some common variable. For instance, I failed to mention that all of our rectangles are in college, and I have a second data set that gives their year in school. Here are the first few rows of this second data frame:

##        Name       year
## 1    Linnie     junior
## 2     Hyrum     junior
## 3    Emmett     junior
## 4  Georgina  sophomore
## 5    Regena     junior
## 6      Duff  sophomore
## 7        Jo  sophomore
## 8  Tatianna  sophomore
## 9   Alfonzo     junior
## 10     Onie first-year

Good ol Duff!

So we have two data frames containing information about our rectangles, the original one weve been working with (which now has 7 columns by my count), and a second one containing name and year in college. We can join them into a single data frame, linked by Name as follows:

df_big <- left_join(df,df2,by='Name')

Notice the new data frame has 8 variables. Here are the first few rows

df_big |> slice(1:10) 
##        Name Hand length width  color     area perimeter       year
## 1    Linnie  (R)  10.70 13.74 yellow 147.0180     48.88     junior
## 2     Hyrum  (L)   7.92 11.83   blue  93.6936     39.50     junior
## 3    Emmett  (R)  11.60 13.38    red 155.2080     49.96     junior
## 4  Georgina  (R)   9.46 14.49  green 137.0754     47.90  sophomore
## 5    Regena  (L)   9.22 13.11 yellow 120.8742     44.66     junior
## 6      Duff  (R)  10.02 12.93    red 129.5586     45.90  sophomore
## 7        Jo  (R)   8.62 13.98 yellow 120.5076     45.20  sophomore
## 8  Tatianna  (R)   7.04 13.14    red  92.5056     40.36  sophomore
## 9   Alfonzo  (R)   6.33 12.21 yellow  77.2893     37.08     junior
## 10     Onie  (R)  11.31 14.30 orange 161.7330     51.22 first-year

In general we have 4 options for how to join two data frames. Suppose \(X\) and \(Y\) are two data frames to be joined via a common column (or columns).

  • inner_join(X,Y) only retain rows that match between \(X\) and \(Y\).
  • left_join(X,Y) retain all rows from \(X\), whether or not they match in \(Y\).
  • right_join(X,Y) retains all rows from \(Y\), whether or not they match in X.
  • full_join(X,Y) retains all rows from \(X\) and all rows from \(Y\), whether or not they match.

In our example above, the two data frames matched exactly via the Name column: every name in df appeared in df2 and vice versa. All four of the join options above would return the same data frame. Lets look at a small example to demonstrate the differences between these four options.

X <- df[1:3,1:2]
Y <- data.frame(Name=df$Name[2:4],fav_num = c(8,4,1))
print(X)
##     Name Hand
## 1 Linnie  (R)
## 2  Hyrum  (L)
## 3 Emmett  (R)
print(Y)
##       Name fav_num
## 1    Hyrum       8
## 2   Emmett       4
## 3 Georgina       1
print(left_join(X,Y,by='Name'))
##     Name Hand fav_num
## 1 Linnie  (R)      NA
## 2  Hyrum  (L)       8
## 3 Emmett  (R)       4
print(right_join(X,Y,by='Name'))
##       Name Hand fav_num
## 1    Hyrum  (L)       8
## 2   Emmett  (R)       4
## 3 Georgina <NA>       1
print(inner_join(X,Y,by='Name'))
##     Name Hand fav_num
## 1  Hyrum  (L)       8
## 2 Emmett  (R)       4
print(full_join(X,Y,by='Name'))
##       Name Hand fav_num
## 1   Linnie  (R)      NA
## 2    Hyrum  (L)       8
## 3   Emmett  (R)       4
## 4 Georgina <NA>       1

Recode

Suppose that the color column is an artifact of old data entry practices, back when the rectangles were young. Each color actually represents a region of the US. That is, the color column actually tells us the region in the US in which the rectangle lives:

  • blue <> northwest
  • green <> southwest
  • orange <> midwest
  • red <> southeast
  • yellow <> northeast

We can create a new column from called region that re-codes the categorical variable color to its associated region. To do so we use mutate() and, you guessed it, recode().

df <- df |> 
  mutate(region=recode(color,
                       'blue'='nw',
                       'green'='sw',
                       'orange'='mw',
                       'red'='se',
                       'yellow'='ne')
         )

kbl(df |> slice(1:8)) |> kable_paper(full_width=F)

We can also use the recode() command to edit columns. For instance, we can get rid of those annoying parentheses in the Hand column as follows:

df <- df |> 
  mutate(Hand=recode(Hand,
                       '(L)'='L',
                       '(R)'='R')
         )

Cut

It can also be useful to create a categorical variable that attaches one of a handful of bin names to a numerical variable. For instance, perhaps we want to characterize a rectangle according to its area as either tiny (< 75), small (75-100), medium (100-125), large (125-150), or jumbo (> 150). We create a new column called size_type to do just that, and we use mutate() and cut() to do so.

df <- df |>
  mutate(size_type = cut(area,
                    breaks = c(0,75,100,125,150,1000),
                    labels = c('tiny','small','average','large','jumbo')
                    )
         )

One may want to make cuts at certain quantiles, e.g., perhaps we want to define tiny to be the smallest five percent of rectangles (by area). To find this 5th percentile value, we can run

quantile(df$area,.05)
##       5% 
## 71.19696

About five percent of rectangles in this data set have area less than 71.2. Lets check:

sum(df$area < 71.2)/nrow(df)
## [1] 0.05

Combining dplyr with ggplot

The packages dplyr and ggplot2 are both a part of the tidyverse and can work together. For instance, we can make a plot on some version of the data frame first modified by dplyr.

Question: Make a point plot that shows the length and width of each blue rectangle, and color the points by the handedness of the rectangle.

ggplot(df |> filter(color=='blue'))+
  geom_point(aes(x=length,y=width,col=Hand))+
  ggtitle("Dimensions of blue rectangles, colored by handedness")

Not much association to see here!

rect <- rect |>

Practice Solutions

a) Frequency Distributions with table(). What proportion of rectangles are lefties? What proportion of rectangles in the Northwest are lefties?

table() gives counts:

table(df$Hand)
## 
##   L   R 
## 174 426

And the following gives proportions:

prop.table(table(df$Hand))
## 
##    L    R 
## 0.29 0.71

For the second question, we first filter to restrict to rectangles from the northwest:

nw <- df |> filter(region == 'nw')
round(prop.table(table(nw$Hand)),3)
## 
##     L     R 
## 0.314 0.686

Higher percentage of lefties in the great NW than overall!

b) Frequency Distributions with histograms. Make a histogram of all rectangle widths. Does this plot support the decision to replace all missing widths with the mean width?

ggplot(df)+
  geom_histogram(aes(x=width),bins=11,col='white',fill='purple')

The distribution looks fairly uniform, over a small range (11 to 15 ish), so its reasonable to expect that the missing width values would be close to the average of them all.

c) Summary Statistics. Find the mean width, mean length, and mean area of the rectangles. Also find the standard deviation for each of these variables. Which variable has the most variation?

We can tackle this by executing each value directly, or we can streamline the process with the apply() function, which applies a function to margins (rows = 1, columns = 2) of a data frame.

Means:

apply(df |> select(width,length,area),
      MARGIN = 2,
      FUN = mean)
##     width    length      area 
##  12.98125   8.93265 115.85473

Standard Deviations:

apply(df |> select(width,length,area),2,sd)
##      width     length       area 
##  0.8321452  2.0518735 27.2558086

Area has the largest standard deviation by far, but it also has the largest mean. We might also want to consider the coefficient of variation (discussed on p.22 of our text), which is defined to be stdev/mean.

The coefficient of variation for length, width, and area are:

apply(df |> select(width,length,area),2,sd)/apply(df |> select(width,length,area),2,mean)
##      width     length       area 
## 0.06410362 0.22970490 0.23525849

Even by this measure the area has the most variation, narrowly greater than the length variation.

d) Means by group. with group_by(). Do lefties tend to have larger area than righties? Find the average area for rectangles in each group.

df |> group_by(Hand) |> summarize(avg = mean(area))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   Hand    avg
##   <chr> <dbl>
## 1 L      116.
## 2 R      116.

e) Two-way tables. Is there an association between region and handedness? Perhaps a two-way table could be a useful table here since were considering association between two categorical variables.

table(df$Hand,df$region)
##    
##     mw ne nw se sw
##   L 38 33 38 33 32
##   R 86 92 83 83 82

Instead of counts, we can display proportions by column (margin = 2) or by row (margin = 1). If we want to compare proportions of righties in each region, we want margin = 2.

prop.table(table(df$Hand,df$region),margin=2)
##    
##            mw        ne        nw        se        sw
##   L 0.3064516 0.2640000 0.3140496 0.2844828 0.2807018
##   R 0.6935484 0.7360000 0.6859504 0.7155172 0.7192982

Those proportions all appear fairly close. Visuals can complement tables nicely.

ggplot(df)+
  geom_bar(position='stack',aes(x=region,fill=Hand),width=.8)+
  ggtitle('Handedness by Region')

We can also focus on proportions, not total counts in a bar plot

ggplot(df)+
  geom_bar(position='fill',aes(x=region,fill=Hand),width=.8)+
  ggtitle('Handedness by region, proportions')

f) Square Factor. Use the code below to create a new column that measures how close to square a rectangle is. Then produce a scatter plot of \(x\) = perimeter vs \(y\) = area, coloring the points according to the squareness variable. What information does this coloring provide? Take some time to consider this question, thinking about geometry and calculus I optimization problems if youve done that sort of thing.

df <- df |> mutate(square_factor = pmin(length,width)/pmax(length,width))

What exactly is this square factor? For any rectangle, its square factor is obtained by dividing the smaller side by the larger side. It will always be between 0 and 1. It will equal 1 if and only if the length equals the width of the rectangle (i.e., it is a square). So, the closer the square_factor is to 1, the closer the rectangle is to being a square.

Ok, so how does the code above determine the square factor for each rectangle in the data set?

While the functions min() and max() produce the min and max of a list of numbers:

min(c(1,20,5,6))
## [1] 1
max(c(1,20,5,6))
## [1] 20

The functions pmin() and pmax() provide element-wise mins and maxs of multiple vectors.

pmin(c(5,5,5),c(2,5,8),c(10,5,0))
## [1] 2 5 0
pmax(c(5,5,5),c(2,5,8),c(10,5,0))
## [1] 10  5  8

Now, for the plot:

ggplot(df,aes(x=perimeter,y=area,col=square_factor))+geom_point()

Notice that for rectangles of a fixed perimeter, the area tends to be larger the closer the rectangle is to being square!
